07720nam a22008415i 9781978822863DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2022025186  a(OCoLC)1374540654  a97819788228637 a10.36019/97819788228632doi  a(DE-B1597)647578  a(OCoLC)1355219142  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aHQ802b.A77 2023 4aHQ802b.A77 2023 7aFAM0000002bisacsh04a306.8122300aArranged Marriage :bThe Politics of Tradition, Resistance, and Change /ced. by Péter Berta. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (281 p.) :b3 color illustrations, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPolitics of Marriage and Gender: Global Issues in Local Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Foreword -- tIntroduction: Conceptualizing Arranged Marriage – From Binary Oppositions to Hybridity, Processuality, and Contextual Dependency -- tPart I: Regulating Arranged Marriage -- t1. Nothing “Celestial” about It: Trafficking Underage Brides between Canada and the United States for the Purposes of Arranged Marriage -- t2. From Family Safety Net to the World Wide Web of Immigration Fraudsters: The Evolution of Arranged Marriages among South Asian Canadians -- tPart II: (Re)conceptualizing Arranged Marriage -- t3. Arranged Marriage as a Process: From Premarital Normalization of Arranged Marriage to Arranged Divorce and Arranged Remarriage -- t4. Configuring Arranged Marriage as a Foil to Forced Marriage in Multicultural Australia -- t5. Forced Marriage and “Honor”-Based Violence in Britain: Issues, Debates, and the Question of Consent -- tPart III: Revitalizing and Reinventing Arranged Marriage -- t6 Revisiting Transnational Arranged Marriages among Syrian Refugees in Germany: A Relational Approach -- t7. From Patriarchal Call to Digital Hunt: Transforming “Arranged Marriages” in China -- tPart IV: Modernizing Arranged Marriage -- t8. Family-Arranged Marriages in Globalizing India: Shifting Scripts of Desire, Infidelity, and Emotional Compatibility -- t9. Progressive Traditions, Repressive Victorians, and the Modern Present: Arranged Marriage and Gender in Sri Lanka -- t10. “I Wanted to Choose for Myself”: Changing Marriage Patterns in the Ultra-Orthodox Society in Israel -- tPart V: Diasporizing Arranged Marriage -- t11. Wedded to Tradition? Continuity and Change in Arranged Marriage Practices among British Indians -- t12. The Changing Face of Arranged Marriage in the South Asian Diaspora in Chicago -- tAfterword -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aArranged Marriage: The Politics of Tradition, Resistance, and Change shows how arranged marriage practices have been undergoing transformation as a result of global and other processes such as the revolution of digital technology, democratization of transnational mobility, or shifting significance of patriarchal power structures. The ethnographically informed chapters not only highlight how the gendered and intergenerational politics of agency, autonomy, choice, consent, and intimacy work in the contexts of partner choice and management of marriage, but also point out that arranged marriages are increasingly varied and they can be reshaped, reinvented, and reinterpreted flexibly in response to individual, family, religious, class, ethnic, and other desires, needs, and constraints. The authors convincingly demonstrate that a nuanced investigation of the reasons, complex dynamics, and consequences of arranged marriages offers a refreshing analytical lens that can significantly contribute to a deeper understanding of other phenomena such as globalization, modernization, and international migration as well as patriarchal value regimes, intergenerational power imbalances, and gendered subordination and vulnerability of women.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArranged marriage. 7aFAMILY & RELATIONSHIPS / General.2bisacsh  amarriage, culture, society, diaspora, migration, Africa, Roma, India, Asia, South Asia, Religion, Iran, Turkey, Indonesia, China, Japan, Kenya, Lebanon, Tanzania, arranged marriage.1 aAbeyasekera, Asha L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAguiar, Marian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerta, Péter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerta, Péter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBlock, Sima Zalcberg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrover, Shalini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJulios, Christina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerali, Noorfarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPande, Raksha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetrella, Serena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShanneik, Yafa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTernikar, Farha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVahle, Schirin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWang, Pan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZalcberg Block, Sima, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZeweri, Helena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023